Locality Detail: DE Bay; Port Mahon; near pier
Other Human Int Description: Left Pec flipper and dorsal fin severed
Additional Remarks: Whale was first reported with bald eagles feeding on the carcass, and located at the end of the first pier. Extreme winds and high tides pushed the whale over and between two rows of pilings running parallel to the shoreline. The whale became hooked on a piling at the hinge of the jaw. Due to rough seas, towing was not possible at the time of the stranding, and took place the following week. The whale was towed to the state wildlife area north of Pickering Beach and landed on the beach to decompose above ground. Burial not possible due to the substrate of that area. Prior to that, the whale landed on the small beach area west of the pier so a limited examination took place. Basic morphometrics and genetic samples were collected, as well as photo documentation.The left pectoral fin was missing, and the dorsal fin appeared severed. Subsequent examination occurred on 5/24/17. A gauge was observed near the upper thoracic vertebrae. Ribs were intact.

Locality Detail: Christina River- Port of Wilmington, Berth 1
Additional Remarks: Deceased Humpback whale reported by the port of Wilmington at approximately 3:15a.m. The whale was floating in Berth 1 at this port, presenting ventrally. A ship docked in the berth, before responders could arrive on scene, which delayed the response effort until 2:30p.m.; when the ship departed. An IAP was developed via conference call w/ MERR; Port of Wilmington; Wilmington Fire Dept. As to how to safely and effectively tow the whale and land it. MERR rescue divers performed in water securements, applying straps to tow and lift the whale; Wilmington fire dept. provide 2 vessels to tow the whale out of the berth for access by the crane; P.O.W. used a crane to lift the whale by the straps onto the pavement on docks. The whale was successfully landed at 4:30pm. Incisions were made in ventral area prior to lift to assist with release of pressure from gases. Whale was bloated; tongue exposed during lifting, casual wide spread blood and fluid spray. Whale was entangled with fishing gear, which included orange and white striped bullet buoy w/ #DG9748; and a smaller oval shaped white float; white twisted line; and a smaller section of orange line. Entanglement went through the mouth, w/ bullet buoy at left corner, around pectoral fins, body and tail flukes. Large wound has occurred at lower of mouth with buoy attached. Left pectoral had constriction wounds. Gear documented and sent to David Morin, OLE. Fluke photos sent to Scott Laudry at PCCST, Rosemary Seton at COA> Whale had been previously sighted 2 weeks prior off Iaswich, MA with entanglement in place. She was caught with a weir off of New Brunswick 2 weeks prior to that, without entanglement. Miller environmental was contracted by P.O.W to handle containment and disposal of carcass. It was handled to the Wildlife Conservation area along the banks of the C+D canal (Managed by army corps of engineers) for burial, coordinated with DNREC. Skin, blubber collected. Necropsy could not take place due to loss of daylight and hazardous conditions posed by slippery surfaces and water proximity.
Emaciated animal; see necropsy report for additional details

Locality Detail: Indian River Inlet near Coast Guard Basin
Additional Remarks: The whale was reported as free swimming in the Indian River inlet near the Coast Guard Basin by numerous fishermen who were in the inlet and Indian River Bay. A video was captured by one of the fishers and put on YouTube (http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N6dKBlc-EGE). Later that afternoon a call was placed to Fish and Wildlife to report a possible collision between the whale and a pontoon boat. The boater reported having collided with something with enough force to dislodge his motor, damaging the hardware. He was concerned that it was the whale based on earlier sightings and the historical lac of stationery or floating objects in this waterway due to strong currents. MERR initiated search by vessels that same day and an arial search by helicopter on the following morning 11/23/10. No sightings occurred.
Additional Identifiers: Could not confirm whale strike, however, based upon expert (US Coast Guard) opinion, it is unlikely there would be an immovable object in this area due to the rapid current flow.

Locality Detail: Floating at sea 1/2 mile due east of the point of Cape Henlopen.
Additional Remarks: Unidentified whale was found on the bow of the vessel "Independent Endeavor" when USCG boarded the ship for inspection. The carcass was described as being gray in color, and very "beat up". According to the interview with the operator, the head and tail were missing and judging from the size and shape of the body description, there were no internal organs. One report indicated a length of 25-30 feet while another report described the whale as being 30-40 feet in length. The vessel, flying Liberian flags, attempted to back up while the Pilot boat assisted in dislodging the carcass. Apparently the carcass sank immediately to the bottom when it was freed. As far as we have determined, no photos were taken. Pilot Statio Maritime Exchange, and Cape Henlopen State Park were put on alert for the potential stranding of the whale carcass. Dec minutes: 38 48.22, -75 02.49

Other Collection Comments: Life history, genetics, contaminants, histopathology, sketleton
Additional Remarks: A large whale was first reported as floating dead offshore of Provincetown Harbor on the morning of 5/21/09. The carcass landing on Herring Cove Beach, Provincetown at approximately 1445 that day. IFAW staff responded that afternoon. Due to several disposal restraints, the necropsy was planned for and conducted on 5/23/2009. Soft tissue parts were disposed of at the Bourne Landfill. Necropsy Coordinator was CT Harry and the Necropsy Team Leader was Michael Moore (WHOI). Necropsy summary included that there were two external abnormalities: 1) line and mesh marks on right flank with dermal bruising evident; 2) chronic poorly healed left fluke blad laceration. Internally substantial sub-dermal bruising was evident on the right side from the right axilla spanning along lateral axis to center of genital opening. Lungs were uniformly dark red and wet. Final conclusions await histology results.

Additional Remarks: Minke whale initially reported floating 1/2 mile off Nauset Beach in Orleans by Chatham Coast Guard to NOAA hotline, who notified CCSN. The carcass later landed on Nauset Beach and level a data and photos were collected by CCSN staff. Orleans harbormaster had secured the carcass with a thick line wrapped around the fluke insertion and anchored to a small danforth anchor. Later on that evening, when staff returned at high tide to pull the carcass higher up on shore, it was found that the anchor and line were no where to be seen. Staff secured the carcass with 3/8" polypro line around the tailstock and a homemade anchor buried in the sand above a burm. The carcass was necropsied the following morning and subsequently towed 2 miles offshore by the Orleans harbormaster. External exam indicated an extensive entanglement in line and an internal exam indicated probably drowning as COD. Final diagnosis awaiting results from histologist.

Photos/Vidoes Disposition: MJM D300 and MJM Sony, Coast Guard Falcon (6/26/2010), Provincetown Center for Coastal Studies (aerial)
Other Collection Comments: muscle collected for genetics
Additional Remarks: Whale carcass was initially sighted by USCG Falcon Jet 110 nm east of Provincetown. A team (Michael Moore, Misty Niemeyer) was dispatched the following morning to relocate the carcass from the F/V EZYDUZIT with aerial support from the Provincetown Center for Coastal Studies on board the Skymaster N6263F (Observer: Laura Ganley). Whale was relocated at 1300 by the plane and the vessel arrived on scene at 1340. The whale was floating on its right side. Skull was devoid of soft tissues, the right mandible was still attached but hanging vertically. The left mandible and both flippers were not apparent. There was no skin or blubber evident, but the dorsal muscle appeared intact, albeit dessicated. Viscera protruded on the left side. There were no flukes and the caudal vertebrae had been picked clean. A number of 8-10' blue sharks were present. The animal was entangled in green netting comprised of two types of net - double 1/4" green braided twine and single 1/8" green twine. Both types of net measured 6" stretch and prominent white plastic rings spanned the seam between the two panels. The netting was tightly wrapped across the dorsal aspect across to the genital area on the left side and around the head and wadded up into the throat region in heavily twisted cords of netting. Three strands of line were also found within the gear (3 strand purple 3/8", 3 strand yellow 3/8", and 3 strand 5/16" line). Approximately one cubic meter of netting was recovered from the animal. A sample of muscle was taken for genetics. For more information, see the event report.

Other Collection Describe: Tom French collected bones in 1995 (see remarks)
Additional Remarks: From Tom French (Feb. 2011): This was an adult Fin Whale (sex unknown) that washed ashore in July 1993 on the north side of Nomans Land Island, Dukes Co. MA. It was reported by fishermen and photographed from the air, but never examined on the ground. It was identified by Greg Early of the New England Aquarium who told me about it. I did not visit the island until 1995, by which time the skeleton was broken up and scattered. I collected loose baleen plates, both maxilla bones, half of one premaxilla, 1 or 2 cervical vertebrae including the axis, about 10 thoracic and lumbar vertebrae, about 4 caudal vertebrae, 1 chevron, about 12 ribs, the baso-hyoid, both ulnas, and about half of 1 flipper. These bones were picked up on June 6 and September 29, 1995. I was never given the New England Aquarium's MH #, but that should be pretty easy for them to find with the July 1993 date. From NEAq (Feb. 2011): no records...

Other Collection Comments: skin and stomach contents
Additional Remarks: adult female in thin nutritional condition with >50% skin missing - mostly on lateral and ventral bodies. Stranded on left side - thus NE. Eyes, tongue, ventral grooves absent; posterior to dorsal fin on midline there is a crescent shaped tissue loss that is 72.0 cm x 20.0cm; ~ 110.0cm posterior dorsal fin there is a small, semi circle shaped (15.0cm width) scavenger damage - shark bite?; on the ventral surface proximal to the fluke insertion there is a 10.0cm x 7.5 cm impression that is likely post-mortem - no tissue reaction - not suggestive of entanglement; many internal organs (stomach, spleen, pancrease) were protruding out of the cavity and were all sun-bleached. Minimal brown, liquid stomach contents collected. Along the right lateral body there is a series of linear lacerations only deep through blubber, no associated tissue reaction - likely post mortem propeller strike - no associated tissue reaction. Carcass marked and left on beach. Buried by town next day.

Additional Remarks: From comments: Refloating attempted but animal died during attempt. This young of the year humpback whale stranded alive on 10/18/2002. The animal was assessed visually & through blood analysis on a hand-held analyzer: since the animal appeared healthy an attempt was made to refloat the animal. Backhoes were utilized to dig a trench around the animal to ease refloating with the next tide. Throughout the digging the animal appeared to remain stable (determined through respiratory rate and activity). Approximately 15 minutes prior to the animal's death, respirations began to increase. The animal died at ~1900 hrs. The following morning 10/19/2002 a necropsy was performed. Gross findings indicate that the animal was healthy prior to stranding.

Locality Detail: Floating in Boston Harbor near Long Island
Other Collection Describe: Baleen- NEAq Education; Pelvic Bones- Dave Taylor; Skeleton-SCSC
Additional Remarks: Carcass was reported to the New England aquarium stranding hotline at 0346hr on October 7, 2012. NEAq spoke with the reporting party Coast Guard Petty Officer Pacearn at 0350hr. RP stating that the CG received a report from a visiting Navy ship docked in the Boston Harbor that a large whale was observed pressed up against their ship with the incoming tide. NEAQ later learned that the Navy ship had been docked just north of the cargo/container ship terminal since the preceding Friday. Photos were not collected at first observation due to darkness. CG agreed to locate animal at first light and to collect photo and send to NEAQ. 0730hr CG collected a photo of the whale floating between Deer Island and Long Island. CG agreed to take NEAQ staff and volunteers out to whale to collect more photos, video, and samples. NEAQ arrived at the floating whale by 1200hr. Images and samples were collected. Due to lack of appropriate landing site and effective disposal plan, carcass was marked with orange spray paint and left floating close to Long Island (42 19.917�N / 70 57.974�W) @1310hr. Within the next two hours, the whale was reported grounded just offshore in shallow water off of the northwest shore of Long Island. NEAq headed to stranding site to assess situation. Carcass could not be accessed safely, so it was left on site. Over the next few days, the carcass drifted throughout Boston Harbor, landing on uninhabited or difficult to access islands for short periods of time to a couple days (see attached map). On Friday October 12, 2012, the whale was high and dry on George�s Island. With assistance from Boston Police Harbor Patrol, and permission from Jack Murray from Massachusetts DCR, NEAq staff were able to conduct a second external exam the whale. Full view of right lateral, the majority of the ventrum, and partial dorsum were observed. Additional photos and samples collected. Again, due to the lack of a disposal plan, the carcass was left on George�s Island. The whale remained on George�s Island until October 14, 2012 when it was reported by DCR to be floating out to sea. October 20, 2012 whale stranded on a rocky shore in Rockport (71 Penzance rd). Again, due to lack of disposal plan, and now the advanced decomposition state, the whale was not further examined by NEAQ and left at this stranding site. Dave Taylor was given permission by Mendy Garron (NOAA) to collect pelvic bones. NEAQ education department was also given permission by Mendy Garron to collect remnants of baleen. Following Hurricane Storm Sandy, the carcass was dislodged and landed 1 mile south of 71 Penzance Rd location. November 1, 2012: Under the direction and organization of Mass Fish & Wildlife Dept, the remaining tissue was removed from bones and buried on sight. The bones were removed from the sight and permission was granted to the Sea Coast Science Center to oversee the cleaning and articulation of the bones.

Additional Remarks: Animal reported to NAIB on 10/17/89 at 3:30pm. Attempts to tow whale the next morning by NMFS Law Enforcement and the Coast Guard were cancelled due to wind, an outgoing tide, and a resistant whale. The whale was successfully towed via harnass by MMSC, NMFS OLE, CG, MDDNR, and a volunteer dredger/salvager on 12/19 approx. 1.5 miles off coast. The effort took 4 hours. Whale was emaciated and in weakened condition. Found dead 12/20/89 in oval wash area, just before Toms Cove Hook at 3750 N, 07520 W, on Chincateague National Wildlife Refuge, VA, several miles from release point. Killer whale rake marks, a chopped dorsal, and dark flukes indicated that this was the animal that beached in the Isle of Wight Bay on 12/17/89. Necropsy scheduled for 12/21/89 by Smithsonian and VIMS staff. Burial planned.

Locality Detail: Coastal bay off Atlantic. Stranded on a mudlfat at the head of Turville Creek, just off Gum Point Rd/589 - behind the casino
Condition Comments: Dependetn neonate calf - mother not seen in area.
Photos/Vidoes Disposition: On file @ NAIB. MD-DNR and Smithsonian
Other Collection Comments: Whole carcass entered into SI collection
Additional Remarks: Animal intially reported and videographed free-swimming in a channel behind 130th street in Ocean City, MD (bayside) on Wednesday, February 22 at 4:30. Animal had left the intial location by 1am on Thursday, February 23. USCG and Natural Resources Police on the lookout for animal most of the day 2/23, but had no luck resighting animal. Initial sighting lat/long: 38.438511 -75.062725. A member of the public reported a stranded whale in Turville Creek around 5:30 pm on 2/23, which turned out to be the calf. The mother was not documented with the animal either on 2/22 or 2/23. Animal was stranded on a mudflat at the head of the creek. Tide was rising and Aquarium first responders at the scene able to secure a cargo net under animal with incoming tide and used a boat to slowly move animal to a nearby boat ramp for easier handling. Boat ramp lat/long: 38.356227 -75.160832. Aquarium veterinary staff arrived around 10pm and animal was humanely euthanized due to poor nutritional state and fact that it was a dependent calf. Carcass secured at boat ramp overnight with Aquarium staff at the scene to deter human interaction/scavenging of carcass. On Friday, February 24, the carcass was removed from the water and transported to the Smithsonian Institute by Maryland Department of Natural Resources. Smithsonian froze the carcass whole and intend to CT scan the whole carcass at a later date. Necropsy details and final disposition pending as of Monday, February 27, but Smithsonian to remain in possession of carcass.

Locality Detail: 9 MILES SE OCEAN CITY INLET. FLOATING 5 MILES OFFSHORE.
Other Collection Comments: skin sample for DNA analysis
Additional Remarks: Mark Sampson (NAIB/MARP) went out with Coast Guard to examine whale and verify species. There was some concern initially from Coast Guard that this was a right whale. Mark collected a skin sample for genetic analysis. The whale was relatively fresh and a probable propellor strike on the left side dorsal to the flipper. A call came in the next day, 8/19/01, reporting that the whale was now 9.1 miles offshore just north of the shipwreck the African Queen. A live whale stranded against a jetty a week prior to this stranding and David Schofield thought this may be the same animal. However, resources were not available to tow the animal to shore.

This was a newborn sperm whale - part of the umbilicus was still attached and the spinal ridge folded to the right. Subdermal bleeding may have been caused by birth trauma. The lungs were inflated, so live birth is indicated. There was ~500ml serosanguinous fluid in thoracic cavity and blood in stomach.

Dana paged Susan Knowles (MDDNR/COL) at 0818 hrs and informed her of the stranding. Susan informed Coast Guard (John Grose) who photographed the whale. Upon seeing the photos, Susan determined it was not a right whale due to the presence of ventral grooves. Officer Grose said the whale had short, pointy flippers with a white bottom, ventral grooves, a decomposing fluke and was approx. 22-23 feet long. The winds eventually shifted and the animal was blown back to sea-- there have been no additional sightings of this animal. Paraphrased by Kara Dwyer.

Additional Remarks: UPDATE: October 9, 2014 - On August 22,2014, we received a report of a "second" dead minke whale which came ashore in the Town of Milbridge (6-7 miles across a large bay from South Addison where this first whale stranded). A team went out to investigate and found a dead minke in a state of advanced decomposition and lying with its upper section twisted. We initially gave it the assession number: COA140822Ba. The team managed to collect numerous bones including skull, right mandible, some 12 vertebrae, 16 ribs, 1 scapula, and a few intervertebral disks. In the interim, bones from the first minke (this record)were retrieved by two of our stranding volunteers on August 23, 2014 who also found that the carcass was now gone in Addison. These included a left mandible, some ribs and vertebrae, and baleen which were strewn all over the beach and brought to COA. Allied Whale staff familiar with whale bones compared the bones from both whales. The left mandible from the first whale matched to the "second" whale. This combined with the evidence of the twisted thoracic area on the second whale - cervical and thoracic verts were found from the first whale suggesting this second whale was missing hers and became twisted upon landing in its second location - suggest this is highly likely the same whale. The whale was left at site in Milbridge. Photos from the Milbridge site are included in the photo section.

The whale had landed on Sand Beach in Acadia National Park. It was positively identified as being the same minke whale from Head Harbor Island by photo identification and the sampled area. We towed the whale off Sand Beach on August 22 and landed it with permission from ANP in Otter Cove which is the cove adjacent to Sand Beach. We necropsied the whale on August 24th, 2011. It was a Code 4 at that point and most organs were compromised. We did find stomach contents which included fish bones and otoliths which were sampled. We did not find any broken bones.

Locality Detail: On the extreme southeast tip of Great Wass Island near Little Pond Head.
Other Findings - Descibe: Abdomen popped open and margin edges clean suggesting it was cut
Photos/Vidoes Disposition: Initial digital images taken by the reporting party, Catherine Matassa and copies housed at Allied Whale, COA. More digital images taken by the Allied Whale examiner and housed at Allied Whale, COA.
Additional Remarks: Dan DanDanto from Allied Whale, COA who hiked to the location and examined the whale (and who also identified it as a minke whale) offered the following description in an email: The animal is a female minke, approximately 22' 10" long. It is tightly wedged in a 'thunder hole' like crevice with its tail stock and flukes jammed under a large overhang, so I was not able to accurately string the measure to its fluke notch. There is no evidence of rope, or other gear on the tail stock. Interesting - the abdomen looks as if the animal 'popped', BUT the margins are rather clean and the flank blubber from this area appears missing, so I do not think it can be ruled out that is was cut (perhaps an attempt to sink it, though now I am just making up a story). The protrusion below the left zygomatic arch is, I believe, the proximate end of the left mandible. The distal end has washed, or been flushed by surge, down the gullet. The right mandible is gone. This is quite conceivable given the position of the critter and the energy it is exposed to. The specimen is mostly inaccessible and absolutely un-retrievable in its present location. I think it has very poor value for an educational field trip - to get a good look at it is a little dangerous and a close vantage only has room for 2-3 people at a time. The hike is about 1.5 hours at a good brisk pace from the preserve parking lot, about 15 or 20 min. walk past the humpback skull. The terrain is rough - loose beach cobble and craggy ledge for the portion along the shore (about half the distance from the parking area).

Other Findings - Descibe: Hemorrhagic tissue at left gape of mouth
Photos/Vidoes Disposition: Digital images taken by and housed at Allied Whale, COA.
Additional Remarks: This whale was identified to species by its baleen plates and ventral pleat numbers and length. Hemorrhagic tissue at the left gape of mouth suggested entanglement in fishing gear. However, we put a CBD for HI pending histological analysis of the sampled area. The whale was eased out of the little rocky cove where it initially lay. On June 22, 2015, we heard that a dead whale lay on Little Cranberry Island near Mount Desert Island. We confirmed that this was the same sei whale based on the blubber thickness cuts and the tissue sampling at the gape of mouth. As of August 13, 2015, the whale remains on Little Cranberry Island although we have been removing the bones as they have become available. The mandibles have been recovered.

Additional Remarks: Carcass found on Christmas Day and reported the next day. A stranding team was only able to get out on Dec. 29. Carcass still extremely fresh due to cold temperatures and water - no smell or bloating, little skin sloughing, eyes intact. Photo ID obtained of the ventral flukes allowed us to identify the humpback as "Triomphe" (HWC# 8769), the 2008 calf of "Spar" and therefore the whale was almost 7 years old. Samples taken of the lesions indicative of entanglement were sent out to Dr. Dave Rotstein for histopath analyses. On January 4, 2015, we heard that the whale had shifted a few hundred feet to the west of the old Coast Guard Station on Little Cranberry Island (Islesford). A stranding team from COA visited the site to confirm the move and get new coordinates and photos. New coordinates are: 44.255439 N, -68.213194 W.

How Determined: Describe: This whale has been disentangled three times

Photos/Vidoes Disposition: Digital images taken by and housed at Allied Whale, COA. Images and video footage taken by Jenn Tackaberry of Center for Coastal Studies, Provincetown and housed there.
Stranding Necropsied By: Dan DenDanto, Rosemary Seton, Laura Lyell et al.
Additional Remarks: This humpback whale is the 2004 calf of "Palette" and is named "Spinnaker." This 11 year old female has an entanglement history including 2006, September 2014, and May 2015. Line was cut on both sides of the mouth in 2014 by the Center for Coastal Studies Disentanglement team in the hopes she would shed it. We found an approximatley 1 meter length of rope with another length of line balled up at one end along monofilament line and two small floats in the mouth of the whale. It was embedded in the upper palete and into the vomer. Tissue had grown over the area. This tissue was sampled and sent out for histopathology. Significant necrotic looking muscle tissue was found in the neck and throat, surrounding the left stylohyoid. There was copious amounts of brown feces in her colon. Unfortunately, she was a Code 4 by the time we could get her towed in and examined/necropsied. We composted the skeleton. In examining the skull, we found the fishing line had cut deeply (27cm) into the bones of the rostrum, completely severing the vomer and bifurcating in both the left and right maxilla. The margins of the laceration are indicative of bone growth indicating healing and that these injuries were not sustained perimortem.
Additional Identifiers: Humpback Whale known as "Spinnaker" and its North Atlantic Humpback Whale Catalogue number is: HWC# 8587.

Additional Remarks: Necropsy performed more than 24 hours post mortem, therefore necropsy data were limited to visual inspection of carcass. Large hematoma on left flank, posterior to posterior pectoral fin insertion (about 4 ft), measuring 4 ft. x 2 ft. Separating muscle fascia approximately 2 ft. into animal. Clotting indicated possible pre-mortem cause (ship strike?). Break in dorsal process of L2 vertebra, left side, may have been post-mortem. Substantial clotting in thoracic cavity, indicative of pooling of blood on the side the animal was lying on when found dead. Organ decomposition too advanced for further diagnostics. Cause of death: decay too advanced and evidence too limited to indicate definitive cause of death. Possible ship strike but little supporting evidence (no human interaction form therefore completed). Skin and blubber sections from the upper laceration were sent to Dave Rotstein at Smithsonian MSC for pathohistology.
Additional Remarks: A crew from Allied Whale, COA went out early on the R/V Borealis on July 3rd and relocated the right whale approximately 10 miles SE of Jonesport, ME. Samples were collected and the whale rigged out for towing. We towed the whale for 6 hours at an average speed of 2 kts. With logistics still to be worked out including identification of a site to land the whale for necropsy as well as permission to do so from Maine DMR pending,lateness of the day and deteriorating sea conditions, (not to mention it was a holiday weekend), we decided to release the whale with two large floats and the tow line attached with the planned recovery of the whale the next day with the assistance of Jonesport Coast Guard (CG). On July 4th a crew from Allied Whale went out with CG but were unsuccessful in relocating the animal. Searches were also carried out on July 5th by vessel and on July 6th by NOAA aerial survey but both failed to find the whale. We have had no further reports - until August 11, 2010. See updates below. August 11, 2010 - carcass of a dead whale discovered by a kayaker on Drisko Island, approx. 4 miles west of Great Waas Island at latitude 44 deg 29.24' N and longitude -67 deg 40.268' W. Description of the animal with accompanying blue tow line (which had been cut at the tail stock) and subsequent visit and examination of the carcass on Augst 12, 2010 by Allied Whale staff confirmed the that this animal was the right whale. Two cruises to Drisko Island on September 27, 2010 and October 12, 2010 were undertaken by Allied Whale crew on the R/V Borealis to collect the skeleton.

-Juvenile male Humpback Whale, identified by Newburyport Whale Watch as Venom's 2016 calf. Animal had been feeding on the biomass of pogies just offshore, with other whales, in shallow water off Hampton-Seabrook-Salisbury beaches. The whale was reported to be entangled in fishing net (suspected pogie net) and thrashing around, by multiple reporting parties. The fisherman that reported the whale, stayed with it while SSC staff called NOAA disentanglement team; David Morin. SSC marine mammal rescue manager Ashley Stokes advised the reporting party against trying to disentangle, but when the animal swam towards his boat, he turned the motor off and waited. The whale approached and he was able to grab the orange float/buoy and with little resistance, the whale was able to swim away, gear free. The fisherman maintained the gear for us, and it was picked up in Hampton that same evening by MA Environmental Police Officer Ryan Lennon, maintained in locked evidence with Lennon, and then transferred to Jason (NOAA OLE). -This whale was later reported dead floating off of Gloucester before landing in Cohasset, MA (New England Aquarium's response territory) on 9/7/18. NEAq responded but logistics (the town, mainly) prevented necropsy. NEAq collected photos, skin sample, and measurement. The whale dislodged in the storm surge and showed up again on Revere Beach on 9/24/18 and was advanced decomp by that time. The whale was buried on site.

Other Collection Comments: Limited samples collected by NEAq (histo and -80C archive). Baleen was collected for educational use by Seacoast Science Center and Blue Ocean Society.
Additional Remarks: -Late code 2 / early code 3 minke whale first reported on 8-16-17. Carcass was floating approximately 100 yards off shore. Reporting party sent lat/long and photos. Whale was in exact spot the following morning and appeared to be anchored/moored on fishery gear. The team responded with NH Fish and Game and NOAA OLE to collect photos, limited morphometrics, and a skin sample for genetics. There were impressions and wounds on both sides of the leading edge of the fluke, but unknown whether they were from being anchored in the fishery gear close to shore. Animal was notched on the fluke and LAS. -8/19/17: Whale stranded on nearby Foss Beach; 43.0054, -70.7450. Animal was collected same afternoon and transported via lined dumpster to Casella Services (waste facility) in Salem, New Hampshire for limited necropsy following day with New England Aquarium. -PRELIMINARY CAUSE OF DEATH FROM FIELD DETERMINATION: The documented observations and necropsy evidence suggest that the whale was healthy and actively feeding, but had been entangled in rope, minimally including the L oral cavity, caudal peduncle, and possibly the fluke. Samples for histologic evaluation were collected but it is likely that autolysis will prohibit meaningful analysis. Nonetheless, histology may be pursued with hope of documenting a vital tissue response along the suspected rope entanglement.

Locality Detail: -Great Bay -Landed at 397 Fox Point Rpad. Towed to Great Bay National Wildlife Refuge
Additional Remarks: **HI Case** -Male juvenile minke whale. Initially reported floating at the mouth of the Piscataqua on Saturday 7/22nd, on the NH side of the state line. Estimated to be code 2 at that time. Carcass landed that evening on Wood Island in Kittery Point, ME. Dislodged overnight and relanded on government property by Portsmouth Naval Shipyard (ME_. Dislodged again and we received report of it on shore on Tuesday 7/25th in Great Bay at 397 Fox Point Road in Newington (43.1162, -70.8526). -NH Fish & Game towed the carcass to a more private location; Great Bay National Wildlife Refuge, in the cove by Thomas Point (43.0808, -70.8606) -Wednesday 7/26: External measurements and exam completed by SSC -Thursday 7/27: Limited necropsy / sampling conducted by SSC & NEAq. Animal was then left on site, tied to a tree, to decompose naturally at the refuge. -Level A exam conducted on 7/26/17 revealed the presence of four linear impressions on the ventral and bilateral aspect of the mandibular region associated with sloughing of the dermis and dark purple tint to the underlying tissue. -Cause of death is undetermined. Strong evidence of entanglement, but due to a very limited necropsy, it is not possible to determine if the HI contributed to the cause of death.

Photos/Vidoes Disposition: on file at SSC and NEAq
Additional Remarks: -9/16/18 Reports a deceased minke floating 1 mile off of Rye entangled in gear. Photos confirmed reports. -9/17/18: Whale landed on Jenness beach, still entangled in lobster gear. NOAA, Dave Morin was notified and reported to the scene to collect gear and data. Level A and photos were collected. Plans to necropsy were established. -9/18/18 Carcass was removed from the beach and brought to Brick End Farms where necropsy will take place. -9/19/18. Necropsy took place with NEAq. After necropsy whale was composted on site. -Preliminary Cause of Death from field determination (NEAq). The history and initial external findings revealed whale to be entangled in rope from head to tail and there are corresponding external abrasions and depressions in the areas underlying the rope. There is gross evidence of hemorrhage in the tissue underlying the external lesions, consistent with physical response to entanglement. Based on gross evidence cause of death is presumed to be associated with entanglement, but diagnosis may be modified according to histologic and toxicology evaluation. Histologic evaluation however will likely be confounded in this case due to the level of autolysis associated with minimal 72 hour delay between death and necropsy. -Baleen was collected for educational use at SSC.

Locality Detail: Near Port Monmouth Rd. and Church St.
Additional Remarks: The whale was an early code 4. Due to its stranding location, the animal was towed to Sandy Hook GNRA to be examined (40.436440 N, 73.992312 W). There were four prop cuts running along the dorsal surface of the whale, across the dorsal fin, ranging 4 to 5 inches apart. There were possible line impressions along the right side of the peduncle. Approximately 70% of the organs could be identified with the remaining 30% being liquefied/decomposed. The identifiable organs were easily torn and showing early signs of decomposition. The stomachs contained parasites. The fore stomach was full of dark brown liquid and fish hard parts. The main stomach contained only liquid. The ship strike area contained two ribs that had been fractured, and there was hemorrhaging in the blubber and muscle layer anterior to the dorsal fin. A full necropsy report is on file at MMSC.

Locality Detail: Pierces Point, creek bed approx. 1/4 mile north of the last house
Additional Remarks: Alive. Initially reported on 6-20-2015 in 3 feet of water approx. 300 yards off the beach on a mud flat. The animal became free swimming on its own just before dark and could not be resighted. The next day the whale was found restranded. Animal was euthanized by MMSC veterinarian Dr. Paluch. Necropsy performed by MMSC staff and NJAHDL at local landfill where it was weighed and disposed of. Necropsy Results: "Case summary: The most significant finding in this juvenile minke whale was the severe depletion in adipose stores. Combined with the fact that the gastrointestinal tract was largely empty, the whale appeared to have not eaten for a significant duration. This may have been due to premature maternal separation. The mostly likely cause of stranding was weakness due to malnutrition. There were also signs of shock within the lung and mesenteric vessels, which occurred secondarily to becoming stranded on the beach. There was minimal evidence of parasitism observed in this whale, which was confined to the lung and small intestine. The associated lesions were not considered clinical significant. Lung lesions associated with a morbillivirus infection were not observed."

Additional Remarks: The whale was severely decomposed. This was an early code 4. A probable rope indentation was found on the left side of the whale,and several parallel indentations were also seen stretching across the midlateral surface along the right side.Finally, indentations 1 to 1 1/2 inches apart were found along the leading edge of the dorsal fin. Evidence was also seen in which barnacles had been removed from the whale. Approximately 60% of the organs were identifiable. The identifiable organs were easily tore and beginning to show signs of decomposition. The other 40% of organs were liquified or "soup-like." Several organs were found pushed forward and "piled" anterior of where they anatomically should have been located. The stomachs confirmed that the whale was eating. (fish bones/hard parts found.) The left side of the whale (near the pectoral fin) had evidence of ship strike. Hemorrhaging had occured in the blubber and muscle around this area. Five vertebrae in this region had been snapped (shaved)near the top of their process. The whale was disposed of by Island Beach State Park. Samples of ship strike were taken, but NOAA was unable to secure funding for processing. Bone remains in archive at MMSC as of 2011.

The carcass was severely decomposed. The angle of mouth, anus, flipper, and fluke were all deteriorated with scavenger damage. Only 10% of the skin remained. The muscle layer was autolyzed. Measurements marked ¿NE¿ were unable to be examined due to the whale¿s position or due to scavengers and decomposition. Internal organs were examined. They were in poor condition with many being unidentifiable due to level of decomposition. NOAA requested that only skin be sampled. Two vials of skin in DMSO were collected. There was a trauma area consistent with a ship strike along the underside of the right flipper. The hemorrhaged area was approximately 3ft by 3ft in length at its widest points.

Additional Remarks: The fin whale stranded on 1/23/12. A week earlier there had been unconfirmed reports of a whale floating off of New York. The necropsy was performed the 1/24/12. The whale was a code 4. There was evidence of a ship strike centered along the right mid lateral surface with hemorrhaging found in that area. In all, only the fore stomach and intestines were identified due to decomposition. The rest of the internal organs were unidentifiable "soup". The intestines were ruptured, and there was heavy fecal matter along with a few random fish hard parts found throughout the majority of the body cavity. A section of the lower intestines was decomposed but intact, and fish hard parts were found inside this section of intestine. The blubber thickness was 1in mid dorsal, 2 1/8in mid lateral, and 1 1/8in mid ventral. A full necropsy report is on file at MMSC.

NMFS, NMFS Law Enforcement, and Army Corp of Engineers notified. 08/24/05 Resurfaced near Berth 82. ACOE tied off to a barge for the night. 08/25/05 Carcass brought to ACOE docks (Jersey City) where necropsy was performed by MMSC staff, Riverhead Foundation staff, Joy Reidenburg, and medical students from Mt. Sinai Medical School (NYC). UME protocols followed and extensive sampling. Code 3 animal. Skin was peeling back. Lower jaws exposed, and an opening near the abdomen exposed portions of visceral organs. Penis was partially distended. There was external and internal evidence of boat strike. Severe hemorrhaging along right side of body. Parasites were found in kidney and intestine. Full necropsy report by Kim Durham of The Riverhead Foundation. deg/min/sec: 40/40/12, -74/08/29

Stomach and intestines were empty, but the stomach lining was infested with encysted parasites. Liver was very dark in color, possibly rom decomp. All other organs that were examined were grossly normal. Kidneys and pancreas not examined. No obvious injuries. Buried at the landfill by DPW.

Additional Remarks: The animal's remains were skeletonized, Animal was dead a minimum of 1 month prior to washing ashoe. Skeletal remains indicated that it had been an old animal. All appendages were missing. Animal was to be taken to landfill my the town.

This animal was found on the bow of the ship Lapis Arrow upon arrival into port. At that time, Coast Guard station New York reported the event and sent photos to MMSC. The Army Corp of Engineers agreed to pull the whale off of the bow and tow it to their facility in Jersey City, NJ. The Minke Whale was tied off overnight to the dock. The carcass was fresh enough that it remained fully submerged overnight until a team from The Riverhead Foundation, including Kimberly Durham, and The Marine Mammal Stranding Center, including Brandi Biehl, could arrive to perform a necropsy. It was found to be a code 2 at time of necropsy. The weight was accurate plus or minus 200lbs for scale fluctuation. There was severe shredding along the lower mandible that was likely caused by being drug through the water on the ships bow. The organs were exposed at the site of impact with the boat. The necropsy showed evidence to support that the ship strike was the likely cause of death. Evidence included impact trauma (hemorrhaging and edema) that suggested the animal was alive at time of impact. There was also evidence in the stomach that the whale had been eating recently. A full necropsy report is on file at MMSC.

Stranding Necropsied By: MMSC, WHOI, NJAHDL, RFMPR, IFAW, Smithsonian
Additional Remarks: Dead, code 3. The carcass was initially on the bow of a ship, then slid off, and was later reported floating. Carcass was towed to the Army Corps of Engineers base in Port Jersey. Necropsied by staff from MMSC, WHOI, NJAHDL, RFMPR, IFAW, and the Smithsonian Institute. Necropsy Results: "COMMENTS: The cause of death is confirmed as trauma based on the presence of bone emboli in the lungs. In severe blunt force trauma with skeletal damage, fragments of bone can enter the venous system and travel thru the right heart to lodge in the pulmonary capillary bed. This is a common finding in cattle slaughtered by captive bolt, where then animal is initially stunned while the heart continues to beat for a short period of time prior to death. In peracute bone fractures, often the fracture site cannot be differentiated from post-mortem breakage and sectioning of bone for the purposes of collection. Hemorrhage was not noted in the section of bone examined (Slide 14), however, neither was soft tissue (adipose tissue and marrow) due to post mortem autolysis so the failure to identify hemorrhage is irrelevant. Other interesting findings include degenerative changes in the scapulohumeral joint and mineralization in the kidneys. The cause of neovascularization, dystrophic mineralization and reactive synovitis is likely to be hereditary or the result of previous trauma. These are not indicative of active infectious arthritis. Mineralization in the kidneys is could be secondary to dehydration or a dietary mineral imbalance. Spermatogenic arrest in the gonads could be indicative of seasonal downregulation of sperm production or could be a sign of immature gonads. Spermatogonia were present, indicating that this animal was at least a late juvenile / young adult. There was no evidence of morbillivirus, toxoplasmosis or brucellosis in the sections examined."

Condition Comments: USCG and Marine Patrol not available to assess entanglement.
Additional Remarks: Initally reported to PCCS on 9/28/13 at 14:15 at the following location (40 37.8, -73 11.5). A recreational vessel reported the whale swimming slowly with visible monofilament webbing and rope across the backside with line and/or webbing trailing to 15 feet aft of the flukes. The Riverhead Foundation, NMFS and PCCS discussed the limited options for the logistics of this case and NMFS requested USCG support for further documentation before sunset - the local station was conducting a SAR at the time so resources were unavailable. The NERSC and Riverhead had plans for conducting nearshore aerial surveys the following morning and were asked to report sightings of the whale. No sightings were made of the whale on 9/29 or 9/30. The carcass washed ashore on the morning of 10/1/14 with gear affixed. NYS DEC took custody of gear and forwarded to NOAA Fisheries for analysis. Gear was marked with identification tags. (gill netting)

Additional Remarks: Animal was initially reported to Mystic Aquarium on August 21, 2009 floating outside the Sakonnet Harbor. Due to tropical storm watches and the inability to locate a beach that would allow necropsy and disposal, Level A was not gathered until August 25, 2009 when a location was found. The carcass was then towed to the necropsy site, necropsied, and buried on August 25, 2009. Necropsy findings = linear line marks were seen on the left and right peduncle (~150cm long, 1-3mm wide on right, 7mm wide on left). Left peduncle line marks showed to cross lines, suggestive of a large mesh net. Line impressions also were present over throat grooves and right mandible 1.5m from rostrum and 5mm in width.

MMA was the first organization to respond to the stranding. Once it was realized that it was a right whale, the various members of the right whale recovery team were contacted. The whale was a known individual, ~2 years old, who had been dragging fishing gear from its right flipper for about one year.

Following euthanasia, the animal was dragged to a private area in Dam Neck by a local crane operator who was repairing bulkheads nearby. The necrospy was initially performed by VIMS with help from VMSM and CMC personnel. A follow-up necropsy was performed later that day by NMFS, NMNH, and VMSM personnel. The next day, VPI vet professors and students studied the carcass and took more samples under the NMNH's permit. Data sheets and samples were taken by VIMS, VPI, and NMNH. Buried at south Dam Neck, behind primary dunes.

The humpback was initially floating in a Nor-Easter. We were able to acquire a genetics sample while floating. The animal later washed ashore in Gloucester. Because it was in an limited access area, we were unable to get heavy equipment, did an external exam, took a couple samples and one of the front flippers. The animal was then towed to another location, where we had to leave it during a storm. When we went back after the storm, it was no longer there. The animal was not decapitated as we usually do when we leave an animal on the beach.

How Determined: Describe: Also possible ship strike - external exam.
Condition Comments: Entrails lying outside body cavity. Entangled in a single green line, with some indication of a possible ship strike.
Additional Remarks: Carcass was initially reported by a recreational sailing vessel to USCG Group Portland. Few details were given and species was unkonwn at that time, so assistance was requested from the NEFSC aerial survey team that was flying in the area. They relocated the carcass and obtained photos. A single light green line was seen running from left side near base of the jawbone across the underside and dissappearing under the right pectoral. Resighted by NOAA Twin Otter 10/31/03 at 43 34 N, 69 38 W. Resighted again on 11/03/03, 2 miles NW of Manana Island (near Monhegan) at 43 47.06, 069 22.09. This is thought to be the same whale due to additional photographs taken. Entrails lying outside body cavity. Entangled in a single green line, with some indication of a possible ship strike.

We collected >one biopsy sample (of some kind of horrible tissue) in the hope that it >might be matched genetically to our archive or to one of the other Georges >Bank carcasses. We did not mark the carcass (sorry), but I have a >feeling that it will be recognized if seen again.
